    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "Having addresses as `20` bytes of data is simple: there is no invalidness. Any `20` bytes can represent any address. If you instead use `44` bytes to represent a hex-encoded version of it, multiple errors must be handled: non-0x prefix, invalid hex-encoding. Plus it takes up more than double the space. \r\n\r\nIt may also lead to ambiguity in parsing, e.g. an address scan of `0x112233445566778800`-- this is `20` bytes, but is it the address  `0x3078313132323333343435353636373738383939` or the address `0x00...112233445566778800` ? \r\n\r\n```\r\n00000000: 3078 3131 3232 3333 3434 3535 3636 3737  0x11223344556677\r\n00000010: 3838 3939                                8899\r\n```",
